lagged and excluded from weighted analysis in the Inventory report; it cannot be used as proof of tightening. (b) the Hormuz shipping-risk catalyst is undermined by the Supply Chain report stating it is irrelevant to West African cocoa export routes and showing no confirmed impacts on cocoa shipping costs or port metrics.\n\nThe “priced in” check also favors the bear: the 24h change is only modestly positive and the 5-day move is strong, but the fundamental catalysts cited by the bear (origin stockpile clearance, demand weakness) are ongoing conditions rather than one-off headlines—so a short-term rally does not invalidate them. Conversely, the bull’s main catalyst (shipping-risk premium) looks both questionable in applicability and likely to fade absent route-specific disruption evidence.\n\nHowever, conviction cannot be rated PROVEN because (i) the market has demonstrable squeeze potential (extreme net shorts and a sharp 5-day rebound), (ii) arrivals are modestly down YoY (Supply Chain), which can complicate the “glut” story at the margin, and (iii) options are expensive with pronounced downside skew (Volatility report), which triggers a required downgrade of thesis_strength by one level—keeping this at PLAUSIBLE rather than higher. [Consensus ALIGNED (Vote=BEARISH)] [VOL WARNING: Options expensive. Spread costs elevated. Thesis: PLAUSIBLE]', 'regime': 'HIGH_VOLATILITY', 'volatility_sentiment': 'BEARISH', 'confidence': 0.8, 'price': 3437.0, 'sma_200': 6096.145, 'expected_price': 3437.0, 'predicted_return': 0.0, 'thesis_strength': 'PLAUSIBLE', 'conviction_multiplier': 1.0}]
